ce:section.ce:para:
To evaluate the selectivity of the present detection system, the fluorescence spectra in the presence of representative metal ions were investigated under pH 7.0 condition at 320 nm excitation, including Co2+, Cd2+, Cu2+, Ca2+, Fe3+, Ba2+, Mg2+, Zn2+, Mn2+, K+, Al3+, Na+, Hg2+, Pb2+, Fe2+, and Ag+, as shown in Fig. 4
                        A. Among all metal ions, Fe3+ shows maximum quenching effect with CDs and is able to quench FL intensity ∼ 85%. Moreover, no obvious interference of other metal ions is observed even with high concentrations (up to 300 μM). The Fe3+ ion sensing capacity of as-prepared CDs was investigated in the range of 1.0 × 10−6 M to 3.0 × 10−4 M. With increasing Fe3+ ions concentration, as shown in Fig. 4B, the fluorescence intensity of CDs decreases progressively, revealing that the sensing system is sensitive to Fe3+ concentration. Insert in Fig. 4B presents the quenching efficiency (ΔF = F0 − F, where F and F0 are the fluorescence intensities of the CDs in the presence and absence of Fe3+, respectively) versus the concentration of Fe3+ ions. A good linearity is observed over the concentration range of 10–300 μM. The detection limit of 52 nM is obtained based on a signal-to-noise ratio of 3 with a correlation coefficient R2 of 0.998. Compared with the results using different carbon-based fluorescent probes to discriminate Fe3+ in the recent years, our method showed wider linear ranges and better detection limits (Table 1
                        ).

After demonstrating the capability of the CDs for selective and accurate Fe3+ and F− detection in human serum, the ability of biosensing performance of the prepared CDs for Fe3+ and F− in living cells was further investigated using a confocal laser scanning microscope. As depicted in Fig. S10, the fluorescence of SMMC-7721 cells without the treatment of CDs was very weak under the excitation of 405 nm while CDs incubated SMMC-7721 cells displayed bright fluorescence, suggesting autofluorescence of biological matrix can be neglected. To observe quenching process in real time, we assessed the dynamic effect of CDs fluorescence in the presence of Fe3+ ions on SMMC-7721 cells, the dynamic fluorescence images and signals at λex/λem of 405/450 ± 25 nm were obtained. As depicted in Fig. 6
                        , the CDs-stained cells were added to Fe3+ ions (0.3 mM in the culture solution) at time = 0.0, 10 s, 20 s, 30 s, 40 s and 60 s, respectively. The fluorescence brightness from the cells incubated with Fe3+ decreases gradually decrease as the time passes. With further incubation of the cells with F− (0.4 mM in the culture solution), the intracellular fluorescence intensity could be increased gradually, and the entire process only needs less than 2 min. These SMMC-7721 cells emitted blue (first panels in Fig. 7
                        ), green (second panels in Fig. 7) and red (third panels in Fig. 7) emissions when they were stimulated by 405, 488 and 543 nm lasers, respectively. Compare to other tag reagents, this multicolor emission shows a strong advantage owing to it provides much space to choose the wavelength for observation. These results further indicate that CDs is a capable fluorescent probe for monitoring Fe3+ ions and F− ions in live cells.
